      "solution": "word = input()\nvowel_pos = []\nword_length = len(word)\nfor i in range(word_length):\n    if word[i] in \"AEIOU\":\n        vowel_pos.append(i)\nlast_vowel = 0\nsyllables = []\nfor vowel1, vowel2 in zip(vowel_pos, vowel_pos[1:]):\n    # gap means number of consonants between vowels\n    gap = vowel2 - vowel1 - 1\n    if gap == 1:\n        syllables.append(word[last_vowel:vowel1 + 1])\n        last_vowel = vowel1 + 1\n    elif gap > 1:\n        syllables.append(word[last_vowel:vowel1 + 2])\n        last_vowel = vowel1 + 2\nsyllables.append(word[last_vowel:])\nprint(\" / \".join(syllables) + \" !\")",
      "statement": "Mark is designing an eye-catching way to attract customers to visit his shop. Your goal is to display a word to promote his shop based on his idea:\n\n1. break word into syllables\n2. add <<space>>{{/}}<<space>> between syllables\n3. add <<space>>{{!}} at the end\n\nA {{vowel}} is any of the letters {{A}}, {{E}}, {{I}}, {{O}} and {{U}}.\n\nA word is broken into syllables by grouping <<consecutive vowels>>, i.e. each syllable contains 1 group of consecutive vowels.\n\nIf there is no vowel, the whole word is a syllable.\n\nTreatment of consonants between vowels:\n1. {{1}} consonant: it belongs to the second syllable.\n2. {{>1}} consonants: the first consonant belongs to the first syllable, the other consonants belong to the second syllable.\n\nTo illustrate: (c denotes a consonant, and V denotes a vowel)\n\n`cccVcVVccVVVccc`\nThere are 3 groups of consecutive vowels, so the word is broken into 3 syllables, like this:\n\n`cccV / cVVc / cVVVccc`",
